# TMS 2027 Abstract — CubXL Self-Driving Laboratory Platform

## Submission metadata

- **Meeting:** TMS 2027 Annual Meeting & Exhibition, Orlando World Center Marriott, Orlando, FL, March 14–18, 2027
- **Abstract deadline:** July 15, 2026 (per ProgramMaster symposium listings; extended from July 1)
- **Format:** plain text, ≤150-word body, submitted via ProgramMaster
- **Target symposium:** TBD — pending Edison top-10 ranking across all 108 TMS 2027 symposia (see `edison-trajectories/tms-symposium-top10/`)
- **Authors:** TBD (Vertical Cloud Lab, BYU Mechanical Engineering; Sterling G. Baird, PI)
- **Related issue:** vertical-cloud-lab/byu-vcl#159

## Title

Modular Benchtop Self-Driving Laboratory for Closed-Loop Aqueous Materials Chemistry Using Interchangeable Powder, Liquid, and Sensing Modules

## Abstract (150-word limit)

Self-driving laboratories accelerate materials development, but most implementations are bespoke, costly, and hard to replicate. We present a benchtop self-driving laboratory built on the CubXL, a modular gantry platform running the open-source CubOS control layer with version-controlled YAML protocols, offline motion validation, and a local experiment database. Interchangeable deck modules provide liquid handling, single-powder dosing with manually swappable cartridges, in-line pH measurement, vial capping/decapping, and camera-based monitoring. Together, these enable unattended solid-plus-liquid sample preparation in sealed vials with in-line sensing and full experimental provenance; capping also mitigates evaporation and provides wet storage for the pH probe between measurements. We target closed-loop, Bayesian-optimization-driven campaigns including solubility and dissolution measurements, pH-controlled precipitation, and leaching studies. We discuss module integration lessons, cost, current capabilities and limitations, and how standardized, swappable modules lower the barrier for individual research groups to field replicable autonomous workflows for materials chemistry.

